structure of adpositional phrases -- tOn the form of complex predicates: toward demystifying serial verbs -- tConjunctive coordination in Amharic: some typological approaches -- tLinguistic type and complexity: some remarks -- tB.3 Discovering Function in the Identity of Form -- tConstituent questions and argument-focus constructions: some data from the North-Caucasian languages -- t“A lot of grammar with a good portion of lexicon”: towards a typology of partitive and pseudopartitive nominal constructions -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLanguage description enriches linguistic theory and linguistic theory sharpens language description. Based on evidence from the world's languages, functional-typological linguistics has established a number of thorough generalizations about the nature of linguistic categorizations and their manifestation in natural languages. Empirical studies in these fields of linguistics have contributed to sharpen linguistic theory in several respects. This volume is a collection of 19 contributions from outstanding scholars in the field of functional-typological linguistics that address fundamental issues in the study of language, such as the nature of linguistic categories, the constitution of functional domains, and the form of cross-linguistic continua. Empirical data from individual languages and from typological samples are investigated in order to achieve generalizations about the properties of human grammar(s). Several grammatical phenomena are dealt with including tonal systems, person distinctions, modalities, reciprocity, complex predicates, grammatical relations, word order, clause linkage, and information structure. The structure of the book illustrates the fundamental importance of the analytical distinction between the onomasiological and the semasiological approach to language and language diversity. Both perspectives are integrated in most papers with a dominant focus on either the former or the latter perspective.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 0aTypology (Linguistics). 4aTypologie /Sprache. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aFunctional Typology.1 aAhoua, Firmin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuwera, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakker, Dik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBohnemeyer, Jürgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuzzolin, Pierluigi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, R. M. W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmbrecht, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelmbrecht, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJendraschek, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoptjevskaja-Tamm, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKönig, Ekkehard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuraghi, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalchukov, Andrej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMereu, Lunella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetzing, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoyse-Faurie, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNishina, Yoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNishina, Yoko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabula